04887nmm a2200649Ia 9780801456480DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20152016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)920784842  a97808014564807 a10.7591/97808014564802doi  a(DE-B1597)478667  a(OCoLC)916715144  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE98.S6bN49 201604a974.012231 aNewell, Margaret Ellen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBrethren by Nature :bNew England Indians, Colonists, and the Origins of American Slavery /cMargaret Ellen Newell. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b18 halftones, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Brethren by Nature, Margaret Ellen Newell reveals a little-known aspect of American history: English colonists in New England enslaved thousands of Indians. Massachusetts became the first English colony to legalize slavery in 1641, and the colonists’ desire for slaves shaped the major New England Indian wars, including the Pe" War of 1637, King Philip’s War of 1675–76, and the northeastern Wabanaki conflicts of 1676–1749. When the wartime conquest of Indians ceased, New Englanders turned to the courts to get control of their labor, or imported Indians from Florida and the Carolinas, or simply claimed free Indians as slaves. Drawing on letters, diaries, newspapers, and court records, Newell recovers the slaves’ own stories and shows how they influenced New England society in crucial ways. Indians lived in English homes, raised English children, and manned colonial armies, farms, and fleets, exposing their captors to Native religion, foods, and technology. Some achieved freedom and power in this new colonial culture, but others experienced violence, surveillance, and family separations. Newell also explains how slavery linked the fate of Africans and Indians. The trade in Indian captives connected New England to Caribbean and Atlantic slave economies. Indians labored on sugar plantations in Jamaica, tended fields in the Azores, and rowed English naval galleys in Tangier. Indian slaves outnumbered Africans within New England before 1700, but the balance soon shifted. Fearful of the growing African population, local governments stripped Indian and African servants and slaves of legal rights and personal freedoms. Nevertheless, because Indians remained a significant part of the slave population, the New England colonies did not adopt all of the rigid racial laws typical of slave societies in Virginia and Barbados. Newell finds that second- and third-generation Indian slaves fought their enslavement and claimed citizenship in cases that had implications for all enslaved peoples in eighteenth-century America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEnslaved IndianszNew EnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aEnslaved IndianszNew EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aIndian slaveszNew EnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aIndian slaveszNew EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazNew EnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazNew EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aSlaveryzNew EnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aSlaveryzNew EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aU.S. History.  aBlack and Indigenous People, Indigenous slavery, colonial American history, Indigenous people in colonial times, commerce and labor exchange, captivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145648040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456480423Coveruhttps: